The pharmacist's argument is flawed because it infers from the effect of melatonin on insomnia symptoms that the pineal gland produces less melatonin as it ages. This is a logical fallacy known as post hoc ergo propter hoc, which means "after this, therefore because of this." Just because melatonin alleviates insomnia symptoms does not necessarily mean that the pineal gland produces less melatonin as people age. There may be other factors at play that contribute to the production of melatonin in the pineal gland. Therefore, the argument is flawed because it does not establish a causal relationship between the production of melatonin and the age of the pineal gland.
